column42: PRINTING INK, FLAMMABLE OR PRINTING INK RELATED MATERIAL (INCLUDING PRINTING INK THINNING OR REDUCING COMPOUND), FLAMMABLE
column168: THE SHIPMENT WAS BEING PROCESSED DURING THE OUTBOUND PACKAGE SORT WHEN THE LEAKAGE AND ODOR WAS NOTICED BY HANDLING PERSONNEL. THE PACKAGES WERE ISOLATED, OPENED AND EXAMINED TO REVEAL STEEL DRUM INNER UNITS. APPARENTLY THE LID SEALS ON THE UNITS FAILED ALLOWING THE RELEASE OF THE MATERIAL. THE SPILL WAS CONTAINED AND THE PACKAGE WAS PLACED INTO A SALVAGE DRUM. THE SHIPMENT WAS HELD PENDING NOTIFICATION TO THE SHIPPER FOR DISPOSITION.

THE PACKAGE WAS NOTICED LEAKING AT THE RAMP AND IT WAS OPENED TO FIND A PLASTIC DRUM MARKED AND LABELED FOR "CORROSIVE LIQUID, FLAMMABLE, N.O.S. (ACETIC ACID SOLUTION). TWO OTHER PACKAGES IDENTICAL FROM THE SAME SHIPPER WERE PULLED AT THIS TIME AND OPENED AS WELL EVEN THOUGH THEY WEREN'T LEAKING. THEY TOO CONTAINED THE SAME TYPE CONTAINERS AND WERE MARKED AND LABELED. THE SHIPPER WAS CONTACTED AND A MSDS WAS OBTAINED THAT IDENTIFIED THE PRODUCT TO BE: "EXTRACTS, FLAVORING, LIQUID" UN1197 PACKING GROUP II WITH A FLASHPOINT OF 115 DEG. F. THE FAA WAS CONTACTED AND THE PACKAGES ARE BEING HELD PENDING INVESTIGATION.

column60: Burst or Ruptured; Burst or Ruptured
column168: WHILE THIS 6.2 SHIPMENT WAS IN FEDEX'S POSSESSION, THE PACKAGE EXPLODED, DAMAGING ONE OF THE INNER VIALS OF HUMAN BLOOD WHICH WAS HIV INFECTED. THE SHIPPER HAD PLACED DRY ICE INSIDE OF A PLASTIC  INNER CONTAINER WITHOUT VENTING. THE INTERNAL PRESSURE EVENTUALLY BUILT UP AND THE PACKAGE EXPLODED. THE ENTIRE AREA WAS STERILIZED WITH A BLEACH/WATER SOLUTION AND PLACED INSIDE A SALVAGE DRUM. THE FAA WAS NOTIFIED DUE TO THE SERIOUS PACKAGING FAILURE. ALL NOTIFICATIONS AS REQUIRED UNDER 49CFR 171.15 WAS MADE. THE SHIPMENT WAS HELD PENDING FAA INVESTIGATION.

column58: Cylinder Neck or Shoulder; Cylinder Sidewall - Other
column168: OUR DRIVER PICKED UP 6 150 LB. CHLORINE CYLINDERS AT OUR CHLORINE SUPPLIER. HE THEN PROCEEDED WITH HIS DELIVERIES. AT ATLANTIC RESEARCH IN CULPEPER, VA ONE OF THE CYLINDER'S SAFETIES RELIEVED RESULTING IN 100LBS. OF PRODUCT BEING RELEASED. OUR DRIVER AND 5 ATLANTIC RESEARCH EMPLOYEES WERE SENT TO THE HOSPITAL FOR OBSERVATION AND THEN RELEASED. UPON INVESTIGATION IT WAS DETERMINED THAT THE SUPPLIER DID NOT FIND THAT THE CYLINDER HAD ABOUT 50 LBS OF WATER IN THE CYLINDER. THE CYLINDER WAS FILLED WITH CHLORINE RESULTING IN AN OVER FILLED CYLINDER, THIS CAUSED THE SAFETY TO FUNCTION.

PROCESSED WASTE THROUGH DMP & RETURNED PRISTINE PRODUCT TO SHIPPER.

column62: Improper Preparation for Transportation; Inadequate Blocking and Bracing
column168: ON THE DATE OF 11-9-01, A DART TRUCKING COMPANY, INC DRIVER WAS TRAVELING TO A CLEAN HARBORS FACILITY IN KIMBALL, NE.  A FEW MILES FROM THE FACILITY THE DRIVER MADE A TURN AND SUSPECTED A DRUM HAD TIPPED OVER.  UPON NOTICING THE PROBLEM DART TRUCKING COMPANY, INC SAFETY DEPARTMENT WAS NOTIFIED. BECAUSE CLEAN HARBOR'S PERSONNEL WAS LOCATED SO CLOSE TO THE SCENE, THEY RESPONDED IMMEDIATELY.  APPROXIMATELY TEN GALLONS OF THIS SOLUTION WAS RELEASED FROM THE DRUM.  THE CONTENTS WERE CLEANED UP AND DRIVER CONTINUED ON TO THE CLEAN HARBORS FACILITY.

DRIVER WAS HOOKING SCRUBBER LINE TO VAC PUMP.  WHEN HE REMOVED CAP FROM THE SCRUBBER HOSE, THERE WAS MATERIAL IN THE LINE.  THE MATERIAL CAME OUT AND SPLASHED THE DRIVER AND CONCRETE BELOW.  THE MATERIAL WAS CLEANED UP WITH ABSORBENTS.
NOZZLE ENGAGED CAUSING SMALL OUTAGE WHICH WAS CONTAINED, CLEANED UP AND PROPERLY DISPOSAL.

column168: A HIGHWAY TRANSPORT OF HAZARDOUS MATERIALS EXPERIENCED A RELEASE OF MATERIAL AT 04:55 ON NOVEMBER 13, 2001, APPROXIMATELY THREE MILES SOUTH OF THE TOWN OF  BRADLEY, POLK COUNTY FLORIDA WHILE ON COUNTY ROUTE 630. THE RELEASE OCCURRED WHEN KC INDUSTRIES TRUCKING LLC CARGO TANK K-3 WAS INVOLVED IN A MINOR TRAFFIC ACCIDENT, WHICH CAUSED THE TRACTOR AND ASSOCIATED CARGO TANK TO OVERTURN.(PHOTOGRAPH (1) TO COMPLY WITH US DEPARTMENT OF TRANSPORTATION (D0T), RESEARCH AND SPECIAL PROGRAMS ADMINISTRATION REGULATIONS, THE CARRIER, KC INDUSTRIES TRUCKING, LLC OF 2420 OLD HIGHWAY 60 MULBERRY, FLORIDA IS COMPLETING A DOT F 5800.1 FORM TO REPORT THE RECENT HAZARDOUS MATERIALS RELEASE. A COPY OF THE DOT F 5800.1 FORM MAY BE FOUND IN ATTACHMENT 1 OF THIS REPORT. A COPY OF THE FLORIDA TRAFFIC CRASH REPORT FORM, COMPLETED BY THE FLORIDA HIGHWAY PATROL IS INCLUDED WITH THIS REPORT IN ATTACHMENT 2. THE SHIPPER'S HEADQUARTER ADDRESS IS IMC PHOSPHATES COMPANY, 2100 SANDERS ROAD NORTHBROOK, II. 60062. THE SHIPMENT WAS LOADED AT IMC PHOSPHATES COMPANY-SOUTH PIERCE PLANT LOCATED AT 7450 COUNTY ROAD 630, MULBERRY FLORIDA, 33860 AND WAS BEING TRANSPORTED TO IT'S DESTINATION AT KC INDUSTRIES, LLC LOCATED AT 2420 OLD HIGHWAY 60, MULBERRY FLORIDA WHEN THE ACCIDENT OCCURRED. KC INDUSTRIES TRUCKING LLC'S DOT NUMBER IS 938171. THE SHIPPERS AND CARRIER'S SHIPPING PAPER NUMBER ARE "937542" AND "01909" RESPECTIVELY. A COPY OF BOTH THE SHIPPERS AND CARRIERS SHIPPING PAPERS ARE CONTAINED IN ATTACHMENT 3 OF THIS REPORT. APPROXIMATELY 1 QUART OF THE HAZARDOUS MATERIAL "FLUOROSILICIC ACID" (25%) WAS SPILLED. FLUOROSILICIC ACID IS THE PROPER SHIPPING NAME AND "HYDROFLUOROSILICIC ACID" IS THE PROPER CHEMICAL NAME. FLUOROSILICIC ACID IS LISTED AS BEING IN HAZARD CLASS 8, CORROSIVE MATERIAL, AND IS IDENTIFIED AS UN 1778 IN THE HAZARDOUS MATERIALS TABLE. FLUOROSILICIC  ACID IS A HAZARDOUS SUBSTANCE, FOR WHICH, NO SPECIFIC REPORTABLE QUANTITY (RQ) IS LISTED AND THE QUANTITY SPILLED WAS LESS THAN THE RQ FOR CHARACTERISTIC CORROSIVE MATERIALS. A COPY OF THE MATERIAL SAFETY DATA SHEET ACCOMPANYING THE TRANSPORT MAY BE FOUND IN ATTACHMENT 4. THE DRIVER WAS WEARING HIS SEAT BELT AND ONEC THE TRACTOR AND CARGO TANK CAME TO A STOP THE DRIVER EXITED THE TRACTOR THROUGH THE BROKEN WINDSHIELD. (PHOTOGRAPH 2) THERE WERE NO FATALITIES OR INJURIES REQUIRING HOSPITALIZATION. THE DRIVER SUSTAINED A STRAIN TO THE LEFT WRIST AND WAS TREATED AND RELEASED. A COPY OF THE DRIVERS CERTIFICATE FOR RETURN TO WORK IS INCLUDED WITH THIS REPORT IN ATTACHMENT 5. NO PEOPLE WERE EVACUATED. ESTIMATES OF THE DOLLAR AMOUNT OF LOSS AND DAMAGES ARE: $1.00 OF PRODUCT, $23,466.00 TO THE TRACTOR AND CARGO TANK, $100.00 IN DAMAGE TO PUBLIC PROPERTY (PHOTOGRAPH 3 AND PHOTOGRAPH 4), 7,703.00 FOR CLEANUP AND TOWING SERVICES AND $3636.00 FOR EMERGENCY RESPONSE AND REGULATORY COMPLIANCE ASSISTANCE. THE MATERIAL WAS LOST TO THE SIDE OF THE ROAD RESULTING IN THE RELEASE OF VAPORS BY DISPERSION WITH MINIMAL ENVIRONMENTAL DAMAGE DUE TO SOI

ON 10 NOVEMBER AT APPROXIMATELY 13:50, JCI- MILFORD, VA WAS DELIVERING 4500 / GALLONS OF HYPOCHLORITE TO THE COUNTY OF HENRICO. WHILE SOUTHBOUND ON I-95 IT WAS DISCOVERED BY A VIRGINIA STATE TROOPER THAT THERE WERE DRIPS COMING OUT OF OUR DISCHARGE CAP. THE CAP AT THIS TIME WAS SECURED BY THE DRIVER AND, THE DRIPS TO THE BUMPER WIPED OFF. ONCE THE CAP WAS SECURED, THE LOAD WAS SECURED WITH NO FURTHER INCIDENTS.

column42: NITRIC ACID OTHER THAN RED FUMING, WITH AT LEAST 65 PERCENT, BUT NOT MORE THAN 70 PERCENT NITRIC ACID
column168: EQUIPMENT WAS UNDERGOING A ROADSIDE INSPECTION AT THE SCALE HOUSE AND THE INSPECTOR SAW A DROP OF WHAT APPEARED TO BE PRODUCT ON THE GROUND UNDER THE DISCHARGE PIPE OF THE CARGO TANK. IT APPEARED THE PRODUCT WAS LEAKING PAST THE INTERNAL AND EXTERNAL VALVE OF THE TRAILER. OUR DRIVER PLACED A BUCKET UNDER THE DISCHARGED PIPE AND VERIFIED BOTH VALVES WERE IN THE CLOSED POSITION. HE THEN REMOVED THE CAP ON THE END OF THE DISCHARGE PIPE. NO PRODUCT DRAINED FROM THE PIPE WHEN THE CAP WAS REMOVED. AFTER WAITING ABOUT THREE HOURS, NO PRODUCT HAD DRIPPED FROM THE DISCHARGE PIPE AND THE INSPECTOR ALLOWED OUR DRIVER TO PROCEDE ON. THE EXACT CAUSE OF THE PRODUCT BEING IN THE DISCHARGE PIPE AT THIS TIME WAS NOT DETERMINED. IT IS POSSIBLE THAT THE DRIVERS ACTIONS OF CHECKING THE VALVES SECURE MAY HAVE MOVED THEM ENOUGH TO STOP ANY SLIGHT SEAPAGE THAT MAY HAVE EXISTED. DURING THE INSPECTION, THE INSPECTOR APPARENTLY HAD A SMALL AMOUNT OF THE NITRIC ACID BLOWN ONTO HIS FACE BY THE WIND. HE WAS TAKEN TO A LOCAL HOSPITAL AS A PRECAUTION AND CAME BACK TO THE SCALEHOUSE AND RELEASED THE DRIVER. THE INSPECTOR DID NOT SUFFER ANY AFFECTS FROM THE PRODUCT. THE SMALL AMOUNT OF PRODUCT WAS CLEANED UP BY COMPANY PERSONNEL AND PROPERLY DISPOSED OF.

column168: DUE TO A LACK OF BLOCKING AND BRACING, 1 OF 16 BOXES CONTAINING SAID MATERIAL FELL OFF OF THE SKID DURING TRANSIT. ANOTHER PIECE OF FREIGHT SHIFTED AND CRUSHED THE BOX OF PEROXIDE. WHEN THE UNLOADING DRIVER BROUGHT THIS TO MY ATTENTION, I INSPECTED THE BOX AND FOUND THAT IT WAS SLIGHTLY DAMP ON ONE CORNER AND I COULD DETECT A STRONG ODOR OF PEROXIDE. THE DRIVER IMMEDIATELY DEPOSITED THE DAMAGED BOX IN A SALVAGE DRUM FOR OUR OS&D PERSON TO OBTAIN DISPOSITION. I RECOMMENDED THAT THE DRIVER WHO LOADED THIS AT ORIGIN BE INFORMED OF THE NECESSITY OF PROPER BLOCKING AND BRACING FREIGHT, ESPECIALLY WHEN IT IS A HAZARDOUS SUBSTANCE.

ACCORDING TO THE INFORMATION OBTAINED THE FOLLOWING OCCURRED. WHILE UNLOADING, ONE DAMAGED FIFTY POUND BAG WAS DISCOVERED IN THE FIRST QUARTER OF THE TRAILER.  APPROXIMATELY, ONE OUNCE OF FREE PRODUCT WAS RELEASED. THE DAMAGE TO THE BAG WAS DUE TO A PUNCTURE BY A FORKLIFT. TERMINAL PERSONNEL PERFORMED THE CLEANUP USING A BROOM AND DUSTPAN. THE CLEANUP MATERIALS AND DAMAGED BAG WERE PLACED INTO A FIFTEEN GALLON POLY RECOVERY DRUM. THE RECOVERY DRUM WILL BE RETURNED TO THE MANUFACTURER, PER INSTRUCTIONS. THE REMAINDER OF THE SHIPMENT WILL FORWARDED TO THE CONSIGNEE. NO INJURIES OR EXPOSURES WERE REPORTED. THE MSDS WAS REQUESTED AND RECEIVED.

ACCORDING TO THE INFORMATION OBTAINED THE FOLLOWING OCCURRED. WHILE UNLOADING, ONE LEAKING FIFTY-FIVE GALLON PLASTIC DRUM WAS DISCOVERED AT THE NOSE OF THE TRAILER.  APPROXIMATELY FOUR OUNCES OF FREE PRODUCT WERE RELEASED. THE RELEASE WAS DUE TO A LOOSE BUNG. THE TERMINAL HAZMAT TEAM PERFORMED THE CLEANUP USING LEVEL C PROTECTION AND AMPHOMAG. THE CLEANUP MATERIALS WERE PLACED INTO ONE, THIRTY GALLON FIBER RECOVERY DRUM AND ONE, FIFTY-FIVE GALLON FIBER RECOVERY DRUM. BOTH DRUMS WILL BE HELD AT THE TERMINAL FOR DISPOSITION.  THE LOOSE BUNG ON THE LEAKING DRUM WAS TIGHTENED AND THE DRUM WILL BE FORWARDED WITH THE REMAINDER OF THE SHIPMENT TO THE CONSIGNEE. NO INJURIES OR EXPOSURES WERE REPORTED. THE MSDS WAS REQUESTED AND RECEIVED.

THE CORRECTIVE ACTION PLAN INCLUDED ENTERING THE VEHICLE, LOCATING THE SOUREE OF ANY LEAKAGE AND/OR DAMAGED DRUMS, OVER PACKING SUCH DRUMS AND FINALLY DECONTAMINATING THE TRAILER AND ANY AREA AFFECTED BY THE RELEASE.

DURING THE INSPECTION IT WAS FOUND THAT THE BOLT IN THE LOCKING ARM THAT HOLDS THE MANWAY COVER PLATE DOWN WAS OF IMPROPER SIZE. THE BOLT WAS REPLACED WITH PROPER SIZE AND MANWAY WAS SECURED. USES DECONNED RAIL CAR AND NEUTRALIZED SPILLED PRODUCT. CAR WAS RETURNED TO TRANSPORTATION.

column168: TANK CAR REPORTED LEAKING PRODUCT WHILE STANDING ON INDUSTRY(HOUSE)TRACK. GRAY OIL REPRESENTATIVE REPORTED THAT THEY WERE IN THE PROCESS OF UNLOADING TANK CAR, AS 7600 GALLONS OF PRODUCT REMOVED THE DAY BEFORE(12/19); AND THE ONE INCH ALL CONNECTION VALVE WAS LEFT OPEN AFTERWARDS. PRODUCT WAS ESCAPING FROM THIS OPEN VALVE, AS IF CAR WAS OVERLOADED(PRODUCT EXPANSION MAY HAVE BEEN A POSSIBLE CAUSE). LOCAL F.D. RESPONDERS ARRIVING ON 11/20, CLOSED AIR VALVE STOPPING FURTHER RELEASE OF PRODUCT. ALSO ON 11/20, GRAY OIL REPRESENTATIVE FOUND HIGH PRESSURE AT BOTH AIR & LIQUID LINE VALVES, TAKING 3-5 MINUTES TO DEPRESSURIZE TANK CAR. PRODUCT IMPACTED SOIL WAS REMEDIATED ON 11/23.  GRAY OIL HAS NOW ESTABLISHED PROCEDURES TO ENSURE ALL VALVES & FITTINGS ARE SECURE WHEN TANK CAR IS UNATTENDED DURING THE UNLOADING PROCESS.

column168: BNSF TRAIN CREW REPORTED PRODUCT ODOR EMANATING FROM TANK CAR IN YARD. BNSF RESPONDERS FOUND THE LIQUID LINE VALVE SLIGHTLY OPEN WITH VALVE PLUG  LESS THAN TOOL TIGHT. VALVE CLOSED & PLUG TOOL TIGHTENED, ELIMINATING ODOR/VAPOR RELEASE. BNSF RESPONDER NOTIFIED BOTH SHIPPER & CONSIGNEE OF INCIDENT & CONFERRED WITH SHIPPER TO INITIATE FUTURE CORRECTIVE ACTION TO ELIMINATE RECURRENCE.

AT 0946 HOURS ON 11/06, CSX TRANSPORTATION INC'S TRAIN Q59206 TRAVELING NORTH BOUND WITH 15 LOADS AND 75 EMPTIES, DERAILED BOTH LOCOMOTIVES AND CARS AT MILEPOST ANB 672.8 JUST SOUTH OF REBECCA, GA.  FOUR LOADED TANK CARS OF PHOSPHORIC ACID WERE DERAILED. ONE TANK CAR, FLIX 2524, WAS LYING THE GROUND AND WAS PUNCTURED ON THE B END HEAD. FLIX 2517 AND FLIX 2510 WERE DERAILED ON THE GROUND AND WERE BADLY DAMAGED BUT THERE WAS PRODUCT RELEASE FROM THESE CARS. THESE CARS. THESE CARS ARE SCHEDULED TO BE TRANSLOADED.  THE FLIX 2537 ONLY HAD ONE SET OF TRUCKS DERAILED AND SUSTAINED MINOR DAMAGE. PUBLIC EMERGENCY RESPONSE AGENCIES FROM TURNER AND BEN HILL COUNTIES RESPONDED. A ONE HALF MILE EVACUATION WAS CALLED INITIALLY AS A PRECAUTION. THE EVACUATION AREA IMPACTED ONLY ONE CHICKEN FARM DUE TO THE ISOLATED AREA. THE EVACUATION WAS LIFTED ABOUT 1400 HRS. THE ACID RELEASED FROM FLIX 2524 FLOWED INTO A LOW AREA ON THE EAST SIDE OF THE TRACK. THE RELEASE DID NOT AFFECT ANY SURFACE WATERS. CSXT'S EMERGENCY RESPONSE CONTRACTOR ATTEMPTED TO PLUG THE PUNCTURE, BUT MOST OF THE LADING HAD ALREADY BEEN RELEASED. WITH THE AGREEMENT OF THE GEORGIA EPD AND THE CSXT'S CONTRACTOR NEUTRALIZED THE RELEASED ACID WITH AGRICULTURAL LIME AND THE NEUTRALIZED MATERIAL/SOIL WAS EXCAVATED AND TRANSPORTED TO AN INDUSTRIES LANDFILL FOR DISPOSAL. BOTH LOCOMOTIVES WERE TURNED OVER AND RELEASED DIESEL FUEL FROM THEIR FUEL TANKS. FURTHERMORE THE FUEL TANKS ON TWO EMPTY REFIRGERATED BOX CARS, BNSF 793249 AND BNFE 18441 WERE ALSO RUPTURED RELEASING APPROXIMATELY 800 GALLONS OF DIESEL FUEL. THE FUEL FLOWED INTO A SURFACE WATER ON THE WEST SIDE OF THE TRACK. CSXT'S CONTRACTOR CONTAINED THE RELEASE WITH SORBANT BOOMS AND RECOVERED THE FUEL USING SORBANT PAD FROM BEEN AND Y

column168: ON NOVEMBER 11, 2001, GATX 14701 WAS OBSERVED LEAKING VAPORS FROM THE MANWAY BY PERSONNEL IN THE CSXT YARD IN CUMBERLAND, MD.  THE CAR WAS ISOLATED AND THE SHIPPER WAS CONTACTED.  THE SHIPPER RESPONDED AND FOUND 3 MANWAY BOLTS LESS THAN TOOL TIGHT.  THE BOLTS WERE TIGHTENED, THE RELEASE WAS STOPPED AND THE CAR WAS RELEASED FOR SHIPMENT

column168: ON NOVEMBER 6, 2001 GATX 55386, A LOADED TANK CAR OF XYLENE WAS FOUND LEAKING BY AN FRA INSPECTOR IN THE CSX TRANSPORTATION RAILYARD IN CAYCE, SC.  THE CAR WAS LEAKING APPROXIMATELY ONE DRIP PER FIVE SECONDS FROM THE BOTTOM OUTLET VALVE.  A BUCKET WAS PLACED UNDER THE LEAK.  THE SHIPPER WAS NOTIFIED VIA CHEMTREC.  THE CONSIGNEE, EASTMAN CHEMICAL, WAS CONTACTED AND SENT A REPRESENTATIVE TO THE SCENE.  THE TIGHTENED THE FOUR BOLTS SECURING THE BOTTOM OUTLET VALVE TO THE TANK, AND THE LEAK STOPPED.  NO CLEANUP WAS NECESSARY BECAUSE THE SPILLED PRODUCT EVAPORATED.  THE CAR WAS RELEASED FOR SHIPMENT.

ON NOVEMBER 10, 2001, PERSONNEL IN THE CSXT YARD IN NASHVILLE, TN FOUND GATX 72845, A LOADED TANK CAR OF HYDROCHLORIC ACID, LEAKING FROM THE SUMP. LOCAL, STATE AND FEDERAL AGENCIES WERE NOTIFIED AND THE NASHVILLE FIRE DEPARTMENT RESPONDED.  THE CAR WAS MOVED TO AN ACCESSIBLE AREA, AN EMPTY CAR WAS FOUND IN THE YARD, AND THE CONTENTS OF THE CAR WERE TRANSFERRED INTO GATX 16347.  SODA ASH WAS USED TO NEUTRALIZE SPILLED MATERIAL IN THE YARD.  CONTAMINATED BALLAST WAS REMOVED.  THE LEAK WAS A RESULT OF A LINER FAILURE IN THE SUMP OF THE TANK CAR.

THE PAIL WAS DROPPED DURING HANDLING CAUSING LEAKAGE.  THE LEAKAGE WAS CONTAINED AND THE PACKAGE WAS REPACKED.  UNDAMAGED PRODUCT WAS RETURNED TO THE SHIPPER.  THE DAMAGED PRODUCT WAS PROPERLY DISPOSED OF IN ACCORDANCE WITH FEDERAL REGULATIONS.

column168: LOAD WAS CHECKED DURING REFUELING, HOURS BEFORE 95% OF SPILL REMAINED IN OR ON THE TRAILER.  THE REMAINING 5% RAN DOWN THE TRAILER FRAME AND DRIED UP. column168: BOX WAS FOUND LAYING ON FLOOR OF TRAILER.  IT HAD FALLEN OFF AND HIT THE FLOOR CAUSING THE INNER GLASS BOTTLE TO CRACK AND THE SUBSTANCE LEAKED INTO THE FILLER THAT WAS INSIDE THE BOX AND WRAPPED IN PLASTIC TO SOAK UP FLUID IN CASE OF BREAKAGE.  CARTON WAS PLACED IN A RECOVERY DRUM.
WHILE OPENING ROLL DOOR, BOX WAS PINCHED BETWEEN DOOR AND OTHER FREIGHT IN THE TRAILER.  SPILL CLEANED AND FREIGHT SENT ON TO DESTINATION.
WE FOUND THAT THE LEAK WAS FROM A CARTON OF ORGANIC PEROXIDE.  WE OPENED THE BOX AND FOUND ONE PAIL WAS EMPTY.  WE RECOUPED THE OTHER PAILS IN ANOTHER BOX.  THE SHIPMENT WAS SENT ON TO DESTINATION.

column168: AFTER UNLOADING THE 1ST COMPARTMENT OF A 2 COMPARTMENT CARGO TANK THE RECEIVER AND DRIVER WERE DISCONNECTING THE HOSE FROM THE CARGO TANK AND STORAGE TANK.  THEY WERE TO RUN SOLVENT FROM SUCTION LINE THRU PUMP INTO STORAGE TANK.  AFTER PROCEDURE WAS DONE THE DRIVER STARTED TO DISCONNECT FROM STORAGE TANK TO HOOK UP TO 2ND TANK WHEN PRODUCT SPRAYED OUT OF HOSE. THE DRIVER STOPPED AT A TRUCK STOP TO WEIGH THE UNIT.  HE PULLED OFF THE SCALE AND WENT BACK TO GET THE SCALE TICKET.  WHILE WALKING BACK TO THE UNIT HE SAW A DRIP AT THE FRONT OF THE CARGO TANK. column168: ON NOVEMBER 16, 2001 A VEHICLE OPERATED BY CTL DISTRIBUTION INC. WAS INVOLVED IN A INTERSECTION COLLISION WITH A PASSENGER VEHICLE OWNED BY LONNIE BLUE OF FORT LAUDERDALE FL.  THE DRIVER OF THE CTL VEHICLE LOST CONTROL WHEN THE DRIVER VEERED TO THE LEFT TO AVOID A COLLISION WITH THE ADVERSE VEHICLE, WHICH RAN A RED LIGHT.  THE COLLISION CAUSED THE CTL UNIT TO OVERTURN AND THE BLEEDER VALVE ON THE TRAILER STARTED TO LEAK FROM DAMAGE DONE TO THAT AREA BY DIRT BEING PACKED INTO THAT AREA OF THE ROLLOVER PROTECTION BOX.  MOORE HAVEN FIRE DEPARTMENT RESPONDED INITIALLY TO THE SCENE OF THE ACCIDENT AND CONTAINED THE RELEASED MATERIAL.  SAFETY DEPARTMENT FROM CTL IMMEDIATELY RESPONDED TO THE SCENE AS WELL.  CURA EMERGENCY SERVICES CONTACTED CLIFF BERRY INC. TO DISPATCH A CREW TO THE SCENE TO ASSESS THE SITE AND TO INITIATE THE CLEANUP.  ( SEE ATTACHED REPORT)  THE DRIVER FOR CTL WAS TRANSPORTED TO LEE MEMORIAL HOSPITAL IN FORT MYERS FL.  CTL DRIVER WAS TREATED AND RELEASED THAT DAY.  THE DRIVER OF THE OTHER VEHICLE AND PASSENGER WERE ALSO TRANSPORTED TO LEE MEMORIAL HOSPITAL AS WELL.  THE DRIVER AND PASSENGER OF THE OTHER VEHICLE WERE ADMITTED TO THE HOSPITAL THE DRIVER HAD MINOR INJURIES AND THE PASSENGER'S INJURIES ARE UNKNOWN AT THIS TIME.  NONE OF THE INJURIES IN THIS ACCIDENT WERE THE RESULT OF THE MATERIAL THAT WAS RELEASED FROM THE CARGO TANK.

column168: THE RAILCAR WAS BEING LOADED AT FACILITY.  THE LOADER OBSERVED THE OVERFILL THROUGH THE REMOTE CAMERA AND IMMEDIATELY CLOSED THE LOAD VALVES.  THE MATERIAL WAS CONTAINED, PUMPED INTO A WASTE TANK, AND WAS RECYCLED THROUGH THE WASTE WATER PROCESS.  INVESTIGATION INDICATES THAT THE RAILCAR WAS NOT EMPTY BEFORE LOADING.  ACTION ITEMS FROM THIS INCIDENT ARE TO CONSIDER OVERFILL PROTECTION FOR RAILCARS AND DEVELOPING A PROCEDURE TO ACCURATELY ACCOUNT FOR HEEL VOLUMES.

A SAFETY-KLEEN DRIVER WAS UNLOADING A TRAILER AT DOLTON, ILLINOIS FACILITY WHEN IT WAS DISCOVERED THAT A 55 GALLON METAL DRUM HAD DEVELOPED A PINHOLE LEAK DUE TO METAL FATIGUE.  THE LEAK ALLOWED THE RELEASE OF 0.25 GALLONS OF POLYCHLORINATED BIPHENYLS ONTO THE TRUCK BED.  THE SPILL WAS IMMEDIATELY ABSORBED WITH ABSORBENT PADS, THE DRUM WAS OVERPACKED ALONG WITH THE SPILL CLEAN UP MATERIALS AND SCHEDULED FOR FUTURE DISPOSAL AT THE FACILITY.  THE SPILL PRODUCED APPROXIMATELY TWENTY POUNDS OF WASTE WHICH WAS TRANSPORTED, ALONG WITH THE SPILL CLEAN UP MATERIALS TO THE SAFETY-KLEEN FACILITY AT 16125 NORTH PECATONIA ROAD IN PECATONICA, ILLINOIS FOR TREATMENT AND DISPOSAL.  THE DRIVER WAS COUNSELED ON PROPER DRUM INSPECTION AND STORAGE PROCEDURES TO ENSURE NO MORE FUTURE INCIDENTS.

column168: OUR TRACTOR-TRAILER WAS HEADING WESTBOUND ON I-490 IN ROCHESTER, NY WHEN THE DRIVER NOTICED WHITE SMOKE COMING OUT THE BACK.  HE PULLED THE RIG ONTO THE SHOULDER AND DISCOVERED THAT WHILE IN TRANSIT, AN IBC FILLED WITH 20 DEGREE BE' MURIATIC ACID FAILED ALLOWING THE PRODUCT TO LEAK OUT OF THE CONTAINER.  MUCH OF THE ACID REMAINED ON THE FLOOR OF THE TRAILER, BUT SOME FLOWED OUT THE BACK AND ONTO THE PAVED ROADWAY.  THE ROCHESTER FIRE DEPT. WAS THE FIRST RESPONDER ON THE SCENE, FOLLOWED BY THE POLICE AND THE COUNTY HEALTH DEPT. ENVIRONMENTAL PRODUCTS & SERVICES OF ROCHESTER, NY WAS CONTRACTED FOR THE CLEANUP EFFORT AFTER THE HAZMAT FIRST RESPONDERS WERE DONE.  SODA ASH WAS USED TO NEUTRALIZE THE MURIATIC ACID BOTH ON THE ROADWAY AND IN THE TRAILER.  ONCE RELEASED BY THE POLICE, THE TRAILER WAS TAKEN TO ENVIRONMENTAL PRODUCT & SERVICES' FACILITY AT 230 MCKEE RD., ROCHESTER, NY FOR ADDITIONAL CLEANING AND FINAL DOT INSPECTION.  USED SODA ASH THAT WAS COLLECTED DURING THE CLEANUP WAS TAKEN TO ENVIRONMENTAL PRODUCTS & SERVICES' FACILITY AT 230 MCKEE RD., ROCHESTER, NY FOR THEIR FUTURE DISPOSAL AS A NON-HAZARDOUS WASTE.  THE CAUSE OF THE IBC FAILURE IS STILL UNKNOWN.  INVESTIGATION IS UNDERWAY AS TO THE POSSIBLE FUTURE USE OF A MORE DURABLE IBC FOR THIS PRODUCT.

column168: A SHIPMENT OF HAZARDOUS WASTE DRUMS WAS BEING LOADED ONTO A TRUCK USING A DRUM GRAPPLER. WHEN THE FORKLIFT LEFT THE RAMP AND ENTERED THE TRUCK, THE LID POPPED APPROXIMATELY 1/2 OPEN ON ONE OF THE DRUMS. THE DRUM REMAINED ATTACHED TO THE GRAPPLER AND APPROXIMATELY 1/2 GALLON OF PAINT CLEANUP MATERIAL SPILLED INTO THE TRUCK AND RAN INTO THE TRUCK LOADING DOCK AT THE PAINT STORAGE BUILDING. RAINWATER AND DEBRIS HAD COLLECTED IN THE DOCK AREA AND BECAME CONTAMINATED WITH THE SPILLED MATERIAL. THE DRUM WAS IMMEDIATELY CONTAINED USING SPILL "PIGS" AND OIL DRY. A NEW LID WAS INSTALLED ON THE DRUM AND THE TRUCK WAS CLEANED UP USING OIL DRY AND SPILL PADS. THE SITE EMERGENCY RESPONSE TEAM WAS CALLED TO CONDUCT CLEANUP OF THE LOADING DOCK AREA. THE RAINWATER IN THE DOCK WAS SKIMMED USING HYDROPHOBIC BOOMS PRIOR TO PUMPING INTO DRUMS. THE DIRT AND DEBRIS IN THE LOADING DOCK WAS SHOVELED INTO DRUMS.THE PRIMARY CAUSE OF THE INCIDENT WAS DETERMINED TO BE THAT THE LID WAS NOT SECURELY ATTACHED TO THE DRUM. IN ORDER TO PREVENT FUTURE OCCURRENCES, THE FOLLOWING CORRECTIVE ACTIONS HAVE BEEN TAKEN:  THE INCIDENT HAS BEEN COMMUNICATED TO THE PERSONNEL WHO GENERATE THE TO REINFORCE THE IMPORTANCE OF ENSURING THE LID IS PROPERLY SECURED. PREVENTATIVE MAINTENANCE HAS BEEN PERFORMED ON THE DRUM GRAPPLER TO ENSURE THAT IT OPERATES PROPERLY.  ENHANCE THE EXISTING PRE-TRANSPORT DRUM INSPECTION CRITERIA TO ENSURE ALL DRUMS ARE SEALED PRIOR TO LOADING.

column168: #1, COMPANY UNIT, WAS EASTBOUND ON I-40 NEAR HINTON, OKLAHOMA.  THE DRIVER OF #1 WAS TRAVELING IN THE LEFT INSIDE LANE OF THE 4-LANE DIVIDED INTERSTATE.  #2, A PICKUP PULLING A WELDING TRAILER, WAS TRAVELING WEST BOUND IN  THE RIGHT, OUTSIDE LANE.  THE WELDING TRAILER, BEING PULLED BY THE PICKUP, SOMEHOW BROKE LOOSE FROM THE PICKUP HITCH AND ROLLED TO THE LEFT TOWARDS THE MEDIAN.  THE WELDING TRAILER WENT DOWN INTO THE MEDIAN AND CAME OUT INTO THE TRAVEL PORTION OF THE 2 EASTBOUND TRAFFIC LANES.  #1 COULD NOT AVOID HITTING THE FREE WHEELING WELDING TRAILER HEAD ON.  HITTING THE WELDING TRAILER CAUSED THE DRIVER OF #1 TO LOOSE CONTROL.  #1 DRIFTED TO THE LEFT, WENT DOWN INTO THE MEDIAN AND CONTINUED THROUGH THE MEDIAN. AS #1 STARTED TO COME UP OUT OF THE MEDIAN ONTO THE WESTBOUND SIDE, THE SLOPE OF THE MEDIAN CAUSED #1 TO ROLL OVER.  #1 ROLLED COMPLETELY OVER COMING TO REST ON ITS LEFT SIDE.  AFTER THE ACCIDENT AND DURING THE INVESTIGATION AND VEHICLE RECOVERY, A VERY SMALL DRIP DEVOLVED FROM THE OVER TURNED TRAILER.  THE DRIP WAS COMING FROM A VENT CAP INSIDE THE ROLL-OVER PROTECTED DOME LID AREA.  LESS THAN 1 PINT OF PRODUCT WAS LOST. AN ENVIRONMENTAL RESPONSE COMPANY WAS SUMMONED TO THE ACCIDENT SCENE FOR RECOVERY AND CLEANUP.

APACHE NITROGEN PRODUCTS, INC. MAKES THE PRODUCT KNOWN AS AQUA AMMONIA USING ANHYDROUS AMMONIA AND PURE WATER.  THIS INCIDENT WAS DISCOVERED WHEN WE WERE LOADING LIQUID ANHYDROUS AMMONIA INTO THE TANKER WHERE A HOSE WAS NOT PROPERLY TIGHTENED AND A SMALL AMOUNT OF AMMONIA DISPERSED INTO THE ATMOSPHERE IN GASEOUS STATE.  WE WERE NOT ABLE TO EXACTLY QUANTIFY THE RELEASED QUANTITY, JUST AN ESTIMATE USING GOOD ENGINEERING PRACTICES.  THE HOSES WERE TIGHTENED AFTER THE OPERATOR COULD SMELL THE AMMONIA BEING RELEASED.  IMMEDIATELY THE OPERATOR NOTIFIED HIS SUPERVISOR WHO REPORTED THE RELEASE TO THE NATIONAL RESPONSE CENTER, COCHISE COUNTY EMERGENCY SERVICES, AND THE ARIZONA EMERGENCY RESPONSE HOTLINE.  WE BELIEVE THAT THIS RELEASE HAD NOTHING TO DO WITH THE TRANSPORTATION OF THE PRODUCT, JUST THE LOADING.  THE PRODUCT IN THE TANK WAS 18.5-19.5% AMMONIA.  PLEASE CONTACT US WITH ANY MORE QUESTIONS OR CONCERNS.

column168: THE NON-EMERGENCY SITUATION WAS DUE TO AN UNPREVENTABLE RELEASE OF ACRYLONITRILE.  THE UNPREVENTABLE RELEASE WAS CAUSED BY A GASKET LEAK FROM A "DIP-LEG" FLANGE LOCATED ON TOP OF A RAIL CAR.  APPROXIMATELY 188 POUNDS OF ACRYLONITRILE WAS RELEASED; HOWEVER, THE MATERIAL WAS CAPTURED AND COLLECTED WITHIN A SECONDARY CONTAINMENT STRUCTURE LOCATED AT THE BASE OF THE TRAILER UNLOADING STATION.  THEREFORE, NO ENVIRONMENTAL IMPACT RESULTED FROM THE SPILL.  SEE ATTACHED LETTER (CCC#01-01) FOR ADDITIONAL INFORMATION REGARDING AGENCY NOTIFICATIONS.

JCI DRIVER WAS IN THE PROCESS OF UNLOADING BLEACH FROM OUR TANKER 5106 INTO THE CUSTOMER'S STORAGE TANK AT JOINT REGIONAL PLANT IN LAGUNA NIGUEL.  HE HAD JUST FINISHED OPENING ALL THE VALVES AND HAD CHECKED FOR LEAKS, WHICH THERE WERE NONE.  HE STARTED TO APPLY AIR TO THE TANKER AND AS SOON AS HE DID HE HEARD A POP.  HE QUICKLY SHUT THE AIR AND WENT TO THE BACK OF THE TANKER AND NOTICED THE RUPTURE DISC HAD BLOWN.  THE DRIVER AND THE OPERATOR ESTIMATED THAT LESS THAN 10 GALLONS OF BLEACH HAD LEAKED.  THE SPILL WAS CLEANED UP PRIOR TO OUR DRIVER LEAVING THE CUSTOMER'S LOCATION.

A NEW TRANSFER PUMP HAD BEEN INSTALLED ON THE TRUCK. WHEN THE DRIVER CONNECTED TO THE PUMP TO UNLOAD, THE PUMP WAS TURNING IN REVERSE. THIS RUPTURED THE DISCHARGE HOSE. DRIVER TOOK APPROPRIATE ACTION AND CLOSED THE VALVES AND SHUT OFF PUMP. SPILL CONTROL BEGAN AT ONCE BY THE CUSTOMER PERSONAL. NEO CORPORATION COMPLETED THE CLEAN UP. OTHER PROPERTY DAMAGE ONLY CONSISTED OF ASPHALT IN CUSTOMER PARKING LOT. K&S PAVING REMOVED AND REPLACED THE DAMAGED ASPHALT. THE TRANSFER PUMP WAS CORRECTED AND TESTED TO PREVENTED FUTURE INCIDENTS.

THE SHIPMENT WAS BEING PROCESSED DURING THE OUTBOUND PACKAGE SORT WHEN THE DAMAGE LEADING TO THE DISCOVERY OF THE DISCREPANCY OCCURED. THE INNER UNIT WAS NOT PROPERLY SECURED AGAINST MOVEMENT WITHIN THE OUTER PACKAGE. CONSEQUENTLY THIS ALLOWED THE INNER UNIT TO CAUSE ENOUGH STRESS TO THE OUTER PACKAGE TO CAUSE IT TO FAIL AND ALLOW THE INNER UNIT TO COME OUT. column42: BATTERIES, WET, FILLED WITH ACID, ELECTRIC STORAGE
column168: DRIVER TRANSPORTED A LOAD OF INDUSTRIAL BATTERIES FROM FERNLEY NV. TO THE CITY OF INDUSTRY PA. FOR DISPOSAL. UPON ARRIVAL AT HIS DESTINATION AND PRIOR TO THE FACILITY BEING OPEN (1205 AM). THE DRIVER SMELLED SMOKE. UPON INSPECTING HIS TRL HE DISCOVERED THAT 2 OF THE PALLETS CONTAINING THE BATTERIES WAS ON FIRE. HE CALLED IMMEDIATELY 911 AND LA CO FIRE RESPONDED AND EXTINGUISHED THE FLAMES.THE FIRE CAUSED SEVERAL OF THE BATTERIES TO MELT RELEASING, ACCORDING TO LA CO FIRE INSPECTOR GEORGE BAKER, APPROX. 50 GALS OF ACID ONTO THE GROUND. ALSO APPROX 300 GAL OF CONTAMINATED SPRAY FOAM HIT THE GROUND. THE FIRE WAS ATTRIBUTED TO FAULTY PACKAGING BY THE SHIPPER; USING METAL STRAPS TO HOLD THE BATTERIES ON THE WOODEN PALLETS THAT SHORTED THE BATTERIES CAUSING THE CARD BOARD AND WOODEN PALLETS TO CATCH FIRE. IN THE FUTURE IT WILL BE RECOMMENDED THAT ONLY FIBER STRAPS SHOULD BE USED TO SECURE BATTERIES.

I ARRIVED AT IMERYS ADDITIVES AT 0500 ET WITH ALOAD OF SODIUM HYDROXIDE SOLUTION (CAUSTIC SODA) THE FIRST PERSON I SAW WAS SAMMY JORDAN HE TOOK ME TO THE CONTROL ROOM THAT I NEEDED TO BE AT. THE OPERATOR THEN VERIFIED MY BILL OF LADING NUMBERS AND ALL OTHER PAPER WORK AND SHOWED ME WHERE TO UNLOAD.  I THEN SPOTTED THE UNIT AT OSIS. I THEN HOOKED THE AIR UP TO THE TOP OF THE TANK (496900) AND, PROCEEDED TO HOOK PRODUCT HOSE UP. SINCE THE PLANT FITTING AND MY FITTING ON THE TRAILER WERE BOTH MALES I HAD TO HOOK A 3" DOUBLE FEMALE FITTING ON THE CUSTOMERS MALE 3" FITTING . I THEN HOOKED THE HOSE UP AND PUT TWO OF THE SAFETY PINS IN THE CUSTOMER SIDE AND TWO IN MY SIDE OF THE CAMLOCK FITTINGS. I THEN PRESSURED THE TANK UP TO 25 P.S.I. ASKED THE OPERATOR (FRED WOODARD) IF IT WAS ALRIGHT TO START UNLOADING, HE GAVE THE GO AHEAD AND I OPENED THE VALVES ON THE TRAILER AT 0530. BY 0545 THE HOSE STARTED TO SHAKE SHOWING SIGNS OF THE PRODUCT ALMOST OFF THE TRAILER. WHEN THE HOSE STARTED SHAKING I SHUT THE AIR OFF, BLED THE PRESSURE OFF THE HOSE AND UNHOOKED THE AIRLINE FROM THE TRAILER. WHEN I UNHOOKED THE AIRLINE AND STARTED TO CLIMB DOWN. I HEARD A POP AND NOTICED THE HOSE HAD CAME OFF THE CUSTOMER SIDE. THE 3" FITTING WAS STILL ON THE PRODUCT HOSE. FRED WAS STANDING ABOUT 15 FT AWAY FROM THE REAR PASSENGER SIDE OF THE TRAILER WHEN THE HOSE BLEW OFF HE GOT SOME CAUSTIC ON HIS CLOTHS & FACE, WHEN THE HOSE BLEW OFF I CLIMED DOWN & SHUT THE INTERNAL VALVE OF THE TRAILER OFF. I NOTICED THE CAUSTIC HAD GOTTEN ON FREDS PERSONAL TRUCK (A RED DODGE) AND SPRAYED WITHIN A 50FT RADIUS, WE THEN MADE SURE FRED WAS OK & WASHED HIS TRUCK OFF THEN WE STARTED WASHING DOWN THE AREA AROUND THE REAR OF THE TRAILER. THE OPERATOR INCHARGE WAS BEV VICKERS. THIS PROBLEM HAS HAPPENED WITH OTHERS BEFORE ACCORDING TO SOME OF THE OTHERS IN THE PLANT. AFTER WASHING EVERTHING DOWN BEV FILLED OUT THE ACCIDENT REPORT AND WE WAITED ON GARY HAYNES (FORMAN) TO GET THERE. WHEN HE ARRIVED WE FILLED OUT THERE REPORT AND I CONTACTED FAIRBURN DISPATCH.

ON 11/01/2001 CWX DSR NEAL HENRY WAS REWORKING FREIGHT TO LOAD AS HE WAS FINISHING HE RIPPED ONE OF THE BOTTOM BAGS AS HE WAS INSERTING A PALLET. NEAL COULD HAVE USED CARDBOARD DUNNAGE AND MAYBE BEEN A MORE CAUTIOUS WHEN HE WAS HANDLING THIS FREIGHT. DISCIPLINARY ACTION WAS APPLIED TO THIS INCIDENT,  AND CORRECTIVE COACHING HAS BEEN DONE. ON SIDE NOTE SHIPPERS WHO SHIP THIS TYPE OF FREIGHT SHOULD LINE THE BOTTOM OF THE PALLET SO THERE WOULD BE NO DAMAGE TO PRODUCT.

ON WEDNESDAY, 11/21/01, RINCHEM'S SANDIA NATIONAL LABS SERVICE CENTER SHIPPED A 33-PIECE LOAD OF REGULATED AND NON-REGULATED WASTE TO RINCHEM'S WEST WAREHOUSE. THE WASTE WAS TO BE PLACED IN STORAGE AND THEN ADDED TO ADDITIONAL WASTE BOUND FOR ENSCO'S TREATMENT FACILITY IN EL DORADO AR ON WEDNESDAY, 11/28/01. ON TUESDAY EVENING, 11/27/01, MARK MILLER RECEIVED A CALL FROM JEFF KUBISAK, DIRECTOR OF FIELD SERVICES, STATING THE SHIPMENT WAS BEING LOADED TO GO TO ENSCO, HOWEVER IT WAS MISSING A DRUM, NUMBER SNLA012043 WHICH CONTAINED A SMALL PIECE OF COAL, CLASSED AS A FLAMMABLE SOLID. JEFF AND A NUMBER OF FIELD SERVICE EMPLOYEES HAD GONE THROUGH THE WEST WAREHOUSE LOOKING FOR THE DRUM AND WERE UNABLE TO FIND IT. MARK MILLER DROVE TO THE WEST WAREHOUSE TO HELP LOOK FOR THE MISSING CONTAINER AND IT WAS CONCLUDED THAT THE DRUM WAS NOT IN THE FACILITY AND MAY HAVE BEEN SHIPPED TO A DIFFERENT TREATMENT FACILITY. HOWEVER UPON FURTHER INSPECTION, WE NOTICED THE PALLET, WHICH SHOULD HAVE CONTAINED THE DRUM IN QUESTION, WAS NOT ADEQUATELY SHRINK-WRAPPED, AND THERE WAS THE POSSIBILITY THAT IT HAD FALLEN OFF OF THE SHIPMENT WHEN IT WAS INITIALLY TRANSPORTED.  THE WEST WAREHOUSE HAS A STANDARD OPERATING PROCEDURE(PAIS FORM) IN PLACE FOR RECEIVING WASTE THAT SHOULD HAVE ALERTED OUR DRIVER THAT A DRUM WAS MISSING THAT SAME DAY. HOWEVER, THIS PROCEDURE WAS NOT FOLLOWED AND THE DRUM COUNT WAS NOT VERIFIED UNTIL ONE WEEK LATER.  WITH THIS INFORMATION MISSING IT IS IMPOSSIBLE TO KNOW IF IT FELL OFF THE INITIAL SHIPMENT OR IF IT HAD BEEN MISTAKENLY PULLED FROM THE PALLET AND SHIPPED TO ANOTHER FACILITY. WAREHOUSE EMPLOYEE KENNY SANCHEZ AND MARK MILLER DROVE THE ROUTE OF THE INITIAL SHIPMENT FROM SANDIA NATIONAL LABS TO RINCHEM A COUPLE OF TIMES EACH ON TUESDAY NIGHT, 11/27/01, IN HOPES OF FINDING THE MISSING CONTAINER. ON WEDNESDAY MORNING 11/28/01, MARK MILLER RE-TRACED THE SHIPMENT ROUTE, ABOUT 7:00 AM TO 7:30 AM, IN HOPES OF FINDING THE MISSING CONTAINER, BUT WITHOUT SUCCESS. JOAQUIN FLORES, THE DRIVER OF THE ORIGINAL SHIPMENT, FOLLOWED THE PATH THAT HE HAD ORIGINALLY TAKEN  IN HOPES OF FINDING THE CONTAINER AS WELL.  WE THEN RETURNED TO RINCHEM'S WEST WAREHOUSE AT ABOUT 7:45 AM AND LOOKED AGAIN THROUGHOUT THE FACILITY FOR THE MISSING DRUM. THE TREATMENT FACILITIES THAT THE MISSING DRUM COULD HAVE MISTAKENLY SHIPPED TO WERE CONTACTED AND VERIFIED THAT THEY HAD NOT RECEIVED THE DRUM.  AT THIS POINT, 8:15 AM, MARK MILLER MARKED THE DRUM OFF THE MANIFEST AND ALL ADDITIONAL PAPERWORK FOR THE SHIPMENT SO THAT THE TRUCK COULD LEAVE ON TIME AND MEET ITS SCHEDULED DROP DATE AT ENSCO. WE CONTINUED THE SEARCH ABOUT 9:00 AM BY CREATING TEAMS TO SEARCH THE ROADSIDES FROM THE SANDIA FACILITY TO RINCHEM'S WEST WAREHOUSE, BUT WERE UNABLE TO FIND EVEN A TRACE OF WHAT MIGHT HAVE BEEN THE MISSING CONTAINER. THE TEAMS WERE SENT BACK TO THE FACILITY ABOUT 12:30 PM AND THE SEARCH WAS TERMINATED. A TEAM COMPLETED AN ADDITIONAL SEARCH OF A NUMBER OF HOMELESS "CAMPS" ALONG THE SHIPMENT ROU
WHILE MAKING A DELIVERY,AND OUTAGE OCCURRED WHICH WAS PROPERLY CONTAINED, CLEANED UP AND DISPOSED OF.

column168: COVENANT TRAILER-01929 WAS BEING UNLOADED BY JERRY NEWBERRY/UKC EMPLOYEE. WHEN HE NOTICED A PALLET OF BAGS LABELED WITH HAZMAT CLASS 5.1 HE THEN INFORMED ME THAT THE BAG ON THE BOTTOM HAD A SLIGHT TEAR AND THAT IT SOME OF THE POTASSIUM NITRATE PELLETS HAD LEAKED OUT ONTO THE TRAILER FLOOR. I HAD HIM SET THE PALLET TO THE SIDE UNTIL FURTHER NOTICE FROM OUR CWX SAFETY SUPERVISOR KIM MARVIN. CF PERSONNEL WERE PREPARING TO PICK UP TRAILER (#19-2633) AT THE NORTHFOLK-SOUTHERN RAILROAD YARD (RUTHAFORD RAIL YARD) AT 505 PAXTON STREET IN HARRISBURG, PA. IT WAS OBSERVED THAT A LIQUID MATERIAL WAS DRIPPING FROM THE TRAILER. THE TRAILER WAS MOVED TO A TRICHLOROETHYLENE PRODUCT. ENVIRONMENTAL MANAGEMENT WAS NOTIFIED OF THE REELEASE (E.M.I. JOB #13319). A LOCAL ENVIRONMENTAL RESPONSE COMPANY WAS DISPATCHED TO THE INCIDENT SITE. THE TRAILER WAS UNLOADED AND THE RELEASE WAS LOCATED AT THE NOSE OF THE TRAILER. THERE WERE FOUR DRUMS OF TRICHLOROETHYLENE. THESE WERE INSPECTED AND NO LEAKS WERE DETECTED. THERE WERE ALSO FOUR 275-GALLON TOTE TANKS. TWO OF THE TOTE TANKS WERE EMPTY AND TWO CONTAINED PRODUCT. THE CONTAINERS WERE INSPECTED AND IT WAS DISCOVERED THAT ONE OF THE TANKS HAD A CRACK ON THE BOTTOM. THE PRODUCT FROM THE DAMAGED TANK WAS TRANSFERRED TO DRUMS. THE IMPACTED ASPHALT WAS CLEANED AND ALL CLEANUP MATERIAL WAS PLACED IN AN OPEN TOP DRUM AND WOULD BE STORED PENDING DISPOSAL ARRANGEMENTS. THE INCIDENT WAS REPORTED TO THE CF REGIONAL SAFETY MANAGER BY E.M.I. THERE WERE NO INJURIES OF EXPOSURES RELATED TO THIS INCIDENT.

column168: AT 910 HRS ON 11-17-01, CTS MGR LERCH WAS CONTACTED BY THE RMCC AND ADVISED THAT THE YARD MASTER HAD REPORTED TANK CAR ACFX 88179 LEAKING AT THE STRANG YARD; LA PORTE TX.  UPON RECEIVING NOTIFICATION, MGR LERCH CONTACTED MGR YARD OPERATIONS JAMES QUINTON.  HE INDICATED THAT WHILE HUMPING THE CAR, A SWITCHMAN HAD NOTICED A CLEAR LIQUID WITH A SLIGHT ODOR DRIPPING FROM THE BOTTOM OF THE CAR.  UPON NOTICING THE RELEASE, THE CAR WAS ISOLATED AT A SAFE LOCATION FOR FURTHER HANDLING.  UPON ARRIVAL AT CAR LOCATION, MGR LERCH NOTED PRODUCT LEAKING FROM THE BOTTOM OUTLET VALVE AT AN APPROXIMATE RATE OF 20 DROPS A MINUTE, WITH NO POOLING OF PRODUCT.  INSPECTION OF CAR REVEALED THAT THE TOP OPERATED BOTTOM OUTLET VALVE WAS OPEN 1 TURN, AND THE VALVE CAP WAS LOOSE 3/4 TURN.  UPON TIGHTENING OF THE VALVE AND VALVE CAP THE LEAK STOPPED.  FURTHER INSPECTION REVEALED THE PACKING GLAND NUT TO THE TOP OPERATED BOTTOM OUTLET VALVE TO BE LOOSE 3/4 TURN AND THE AIR VALVE PLUG WAS NOTED TO BE IN POSITION, BUT NOT WRENCH TIGHT.  UPON TIGHTENING OF ALL VALVES AND FITTINGS THE CAR WAS RELEASED TO CONTINUE ONTO DESTINATION. THERE WERE NO REPORTED INJURIES, DRAINS OR WATERWAYS IMPACTED RESULTING FROM THIS RELEASE.  NOR WAS THERE ANY CLEAN-UP EFFORTS, AS PRODUCT EVAPORATED UPON CONTACTED WITH THE ATMOSPHERE. E.M.I. JOB NUMBER: 13670 CF PERSONNEL WERE UNLOADING THE TRAILER WHEN IT WAS NOTED THAT THE TOTE TANK HAD BEEN PUNCTURED BY ANOTHER PIECE OF FREIGHT. THE PARTIAL CONTENTS HAD LEAKED ONTO THE FLOOR AND THE PAVEMENT UNDERNEATH. PERSONNEL FROM ADVANCED RESPONSE CORPORATION WERE CALLED TO THE SCENE TO MAKE A CLEANUP. THE TOTE WAS REPOSITIONED TO STOP THE LEAKAGE AND ABSORBENTS WERE APPLIED TO ALL IMPACTED AREAS. CONTAMINATED ABSORBENTS WERE PLACED IN DRUMS. THE DAMAGED TOTE AND THE WASTE DRUMS WERE STAGED ON SITE PENDING OFF SITE DISPOSAL.

ACCORDING TO THE INFORMATION OBTAINED, THE FOLLOWING OCCURRED. WHILE ON THE DOCK, ONE LEAKING FIVE GALLON METAL PAIL WAS DISCOVERED. APPROXIMATELY ONE OUNCE OF FREE PRODUCT WAS RELEASED. THE RELEASE WAS DUE TO A LOOSE BUNG. THE TERMINAL HAZMAT TEAM PERFORMED THE CLEANUP USING LEVEL C PROTECTION, ABSORBENT PADS AND A BOOM. THE CLEANUP MATERIALS WERE PLACED INTO A FIVE GALLON POLY RECOVERY DRUM WHICH WILL BE HELD AT THE TERMINAL FOR DISPOSITION. THE PAIL WAS PLACED INTO A FIFTEEN GALLON METAL OVERPACK DRUM AND WILL BE FORWARDED ON TO THE CONSIGNEE ALONG WITH THE REMAINDER OF THE SHIPMENT. NO INJURIES OR EXPOSURES WERE REPORTED. THE MSDS WAS REQUESTED AND RECEIVED.

column168: CSX TRANSPORTATION PERSONNEL AT EDGEWOOD YARD IN JACKSONVILLE, FL REPORTED A STRONG ODOR COMING FROM THE DIRECTION OF SEVERAL TANK CARS. CSXT HAZARDOUS MATERIALS MANAGER, E.G. COOK RESPONDED. INSPECTED UTLX 663303, RESIDUE LAST CONTAINED COMBUSTIBLE LIQUID NOS (PINE OIL), THOUGHT BE THE SOURCE OF THE ODORS. THIS CAR HAD NO SIGN OF ANY LEAKAGE. SEVERAL OTHER TANK CARS WERE CHECKED AND IT WAS DETERMINED THAT THE ODOR WAS COME FROM AN ACFX 79860, LOAD FLAMMABLE LIQUID NOS (TURPENTINE RESIDUE). THIS INSPECTOR DISCOVERED VAPORS COMING FROM AROUND THE PACKING GLAND OF THE OPERATING ROD FOR THE TOP OPERATED BOTTOM OUTLET VALVE. THE PACKING GLAND NUT WAS WRENCH TIGHT BUT THE OPERATING ROD COULD BE TURNED BY HAND . THE NUT WAS REMOVED AND ADDITIONAL TEFLON PACKING MATERIAL WAS INSTALLED. THE VALVE WAS CONFIRMED TO BE CLOSED AND THE PACKING GLAND NUT WAS INSTALLED WRENCH TIGHT.  THE VAPOR LEAK STOPPED AND THE CAR WAS RELEASED. THE SHIPPER WAS NOTIFIED VIA CHEMTREC.

ON MONDAY, 11/5/01, TANK CAR GATX 57077 WAS FOUND TO BE LEAKING A SMALL AMOUNT OF LIQUID FROM THE TOP OF THE CAR.  THE CAR WAS IN UNION PACIFIC RAILROAD TRAIN MKCLI-03 ON THE MAIN LINE IN THE MONROE, LA. YARD.  THE CAR WAS THEN ISOLATED.  AGENCIES RESPONDING TO THE INCIDENT INCLUDED THE MONROE FIRE DEPT., THE LOUISIANA STATE POLICE, THE LOUISIANA DEPT. OF EVN. QUALITY.  RESPONSE BY UNION PACIFIC RAILROAD PERSONNEL INCLUDED SR. SPECIAL AGENT HAZ/MAT ED FEDRICK.  FEDRICK AND LSP SGT. ED BOBBIT INSPECTED THE CAR AND FOUND THE LEAKAGE TO BE COMING FROM THE LIQUID VALVE ON TOP OF THE CAR. THE AIR INLET VALVE WAS OPENED AND BUILT UP VAPOR PRESSURE WAS BLED OFF. THIS STOPPED THE CAR FROM LEAKING.  THE CAR REMAINED AT THE MONROE YARD UNTIL THE NEXT DAY AND ON TUESDAY, 11/6/01, DOW CHEMICAL, THE SHIPPER SENT MR. DWAYNE LEBLANC AND SEVERAL OTHER TECHNICIANS ALONG WITH PERSONNEL FROM HULCHER SERVICES.  THE LOAD WAS REDUCED APPROXIMATELY 2074 GALLONS INTO A TANK TRUCK AND THE LIQUID VALVE PLUG WAS SECURED TO PREVENT LEAKAGE.  THE SMALL AMOUNT OF SPILLAGE THAT CONTACTED THE BALLAST EVAPORATED AND DID NOT REQUIRE ANY ADDITIONAL REMEDIATION.  AS A PRECAUTION, THE MONROE FIRE DEPT. HAD EVACUATED THE RESIDENTS OF ABOUT 5 HOMES IN THE IMMEDIATE VICINITY FOR APPROXIMATELY 2 HOURS, DURING THE INITIAL RESPONSE TO THE INCIDENT.

column168: AT APPROXIMATELY 2100 HOURS CTS MANAGER ROBERT BAVIER RESPONDED TO ICTF FOR A REPORTED LEAKING INTERMODAL CONTAINER.  BAVIER'S INSPECTION DETERMINED THAT THE CONTAINER WAS LEAKING.  AN ATTEMPT WAS MADE TO CONTACT THE SHIPPER THROUGH CHEMTREC.  CHEMTREC STATED THAT NEDLLOYD WAS NOT A MEMBER.  THE CONTAINER WAS OPENED TO RETRIEVE THE SHIPPING PAPERS.  THE SHIPPER IS SCHIRM USA WHICH IS A TOLLER FOR MONSANTO CHEMICAL.  CHEMTREC WAS CONTACTED AND CONTACT WAS MADE WITH MONSANTO BUT NO CONFIRMATION OF OWNERSHIP WAS MADE.  ALL PHONE NUMBERS ON THE SHIPPING DOCUMENT MINUS THE OVERSEAS NUMBER WERE CALLED INCLUDING INFORMATION ASSISTANCE ON SCHIRM USA.  ONLY ONE NUMBER HAD AN ANSWERING MACHINE.  ON THE FOLLOWING DAY MONSANTO RESPONDED TO BAVIER'S CALL AND ACCEPTED RESPONSIBILITY.  ENVIRONMENTAL TRANSLOADING SERVICE WAS CONTRACTED TO RESPOND TO CLEANUP THE CONTAINER AND FLAT CAR. ON NOVEMBER 5TH, THE CONTAINER WAS OFF-LOADED.  IT WAS DETERMINED THAT ONE 55-GALLON DRUM HAD A SMALL HOLE.  APPROXIMATELY 20 GALLONS HAD LEAKED FROM THE DRUM.

MR O'BRIEN INSPECTED THE REMAINING FITTINGS AND FOUND ALL SECURE.  THE PLUG ON THE LEAKING LIQUID LINE WAS TIGHTENED APPROXIMATELY 3/4 OF ONE TURN.

ON THE MORNING OF MONDAY, NOVEMBER 19, 2001 AT APPROXIMATELY 0735 A LOUD NOISE WAS HEARD FROM THE NORTHEASTERN AREA OF THE HAZARDOUS WASTE STORAGE WAREHOUSE OF ENSCO WILMINGTON (SEE MAP). ENSCO WILMINGTON  IS A RCRA PERMITTED TREATMENT, STORAGE AND DISPOSAL FACILITY, LOCATED AT 1737 EAST DENNI STREET, WILMINGTON,  CA 90744 (EPA #: CAD 044 429 835). SEVERAL ENSCO EMPLOYEES WHO WERE ON BREAK IN THE LUNCHROOM AT THE TIME HEARD THE NOISE( SEE MAP). VAPOR WAS SEEN COMING FROM A TRAILER STAGED AT THE LOADING/ UNLOADING DOCK.  THE TRAILER'S CONTENT CONSISTED OF A CONSOLIDATED LOAD OF 10-DAY TRANSFER MATERIAL, WHICH INCLUDED WASTE TRANSPORTED TO THE FACILITY BY ENSCO'S TRANSPORTATION FLEET, THAT OPERATES UNDER THE DBA DIVISION TRANSPORT(EPA#: ARD 069 748 192).  THERE WERE APPROXIMATELY 30 CONTAINERS ON THE TRUCK AT THE TIME OF THE INCIDENT. THE SUSPECTED CONTAINER WAS IMMEDIATELY IDENTIFIED AS BEING A CAUSTIC WASTE THAT SOME HOW OVER PRESSURIZED, CAUSING THE TOP OF AN OPEN-TOP 55- GALLON FIBER (POLY) DRUM TO POP OFF (SEE MANIFEST AR1188246 LINE 11B.) THE PRESSURE WAS STRONG ENOUGH TO CAUSE APPROXIMATELY 20 GALLONS OF THE MATERIAL INSIDE OF THE DRUM TO SPEW ONTO THE CEILING, WALLS AND FLOOR OF THE TRAILER.  AN INDUSTRIAL FAN WAS USED TO EXPEDITE THE PROCESS OF VENTING THE TRAILER TO INCREASE VISIBILITY. ENSCO Wilmington EMERGENCY RESPONSE PERSONNEL IMMEDIATELY DONNED LEVEL-B PPE AND ENTERED THE TRAILER. ER PERSONNEL LOCATED THE DRUM, WHICH WAS MISSING ITS LID. THE LID WAS PLACED ONTO THE CONTAINER AND IT ALONG WITH THREE OTHERS MANIFESTED ON THE SAME LINE ITEM WERE PALLETIZED (SEE PICTURE) AND PLACED INTO THE REPACKAGING AREA "D" OF THE ENSCO Wilmington WASTE STORAGE WAREHOUSE (SEE MAP). THIS AREA IS EQUIPPED WITH FUME HOODS, DESIGNATED FOR VENTING DRUMS. ONCE THE DRUMS WERE REMOVED, ER PERSONNEL PROCEEDED TO DECONTAMINATE THE TRAILER AND REMAINING CONTAINERS (SEE PICTURES). RAGS WERE USED TO REMOVE SPILLED MATERIAL FROM THE TRAILER'S CEILING, WALLS AND REMAINING CONTAINERS. THE FLOOR OF THE TRAILER WAS CLEANED WITH PRESSURIZED STREAM, WITH THE LIQUID RUN-OFF BEING PLACED INTO DRUMS AND MANAGED AS HAZARDOUS WASTE.  THE WASTE PROFILE OF THE CAUSTIC MATERIAL WAS RETRIEVED AND DID NOT GIVE ANY INDICATION OF REACTIVE CONSTITUENTS THAT WOULD CAUSE PRESSURE TO BUILD SO FORCEFULLY INSIDE OF A DRUM.  A CALL WAS THEN PLACED TO THE GENERATOR CONTACT LISTED ON THE MANIFEST. THE CONTACT DETERMINED THE POSSIBLE SCENARIO THAT CAUSED INCOMPATIBLE CONSTITUENTS TO BE PLACED INTO THIS PARTICULAR CONTAINER. HE INDICATED THAT THE WASTE SHOULD HAVE CONTAINED ARSENIC, HYDROGEN PEROXIDE AND SODIUM HYDROXIDE. ANOTHER WASTE STREAM THAT IS GENERATED IN THAT SAME AREA CONTAINED ARSENIC DUST, SEDIMENT, HYDROGEN PEROXIDE AND CAUSTIC. HE STATED THAT PRIOR TO SHIPPING THE LATTER STREAM, HE WOULD USUALLY TREAT IT IN A MANNER CAUSING A NON-EXOTHERMIC REACTION, RESULTING IN MATERIAL THAT IS STABILIZED FOR SHIPMENT. HE SAID THAT WITHOUT THIS TREATMENT PROCESS, IT IS POSSIBLE THAT PRESSURE

column168: ON 11-23-01, MY DRIVER WAS TRAVELING EAST ON HWY 252 IN HONEA PATH, SOUTH CAROLINA, ALONG WITH ANOTHER VEHICLE. HE PUT ON HIS LEFT HAND BLINKER, WHILE IN A PASSING LANE, AND PROCEEDED TO GO AROUND THE OTHER VEHICLE, WHICH WAS TRAVELING EXTREMELY SLOW AND HAD NO LIGHTS OR TURNING SIGNALS. WHEN HE GOT UP NEXT TO THE OTHER VEHICLE, THE OTHER DRIVER TURNED INTO OUR TRUCK, WHILE ATTEMPTING TO TURN INTO A DRIVEWAY. OUR TRUCK'S RIGHT FRONT BUMPER HIT HER LEFT FRONT FENDER BETWEEN THE TIRE AND THE ODOR, CAUSING THE DRIVER TO LOOSE CONTROL OF HER VEHICLE AND LANDING ON THE SIDE OF THE ROAD, SHE WAS EJECTED FROM THE VEHICLE, AND HER CONTIN VEHICLE CAUGHT FIRE-COMPLETELY DESTROYING HER VEHICLE. OUR TRUCK WENT DOWN INTO A DITCH AND COMPLETELY FLIPPED OVER, LANDING ON ITS OTHER SIDE IN THE MIDDLE OF THE ROAD. BOTH DRIVERS WERE TAKEN TO THE HOSPITAL WITH MINOR INJURIES AND WERE RELEASED THE SAME DAY. OUR TRACTOR TRUCK AND PETROLEUM TRAILER WERE TOTALED.  WHEN THE ACCIDENT WAS DISCOVERED, THE FIRE DEPARTMENT AND EMERGENCY AGENCIES WERE NOTIFIED AND DISPATCHED TO THE SCENE, AS WELL AS OUR SAFETY MANAGER, ANTHONY KNOWLES. THE APPROPRIATE DHEC & EPA OFFICES WERE ALSO NOTIFIED.  WE HAVE HAD SAFETY MEETINGS WITH OUR DRIVERS ABOUT OUR ACCIDENT RECORD AND STRESSED TO THEM THE IMPORTANCE OF BEING MORE CAREFUL AND ALERT WHILE ON THEIR SHIFT. WE HAVE IMPLEMENTED A SAFETY BONUS PROGRAM, AND PENALIZE THOSE WHO HAVE ADDCIDENTS. WE WILL CONTINUE TO HAVE THESE SAFETY MEETINGS AND TRY OUR BEST TO MINIMIZE OUR ACCIDENTS.

THE TRUCK WAS PRE-SET TO PUMP THE NUMBER OF GALLONS ORDERED. THE TRUCK SHUT OFF AT THE GALLONAGE ORDERED. CUSTOMER HAD MISJUDGED THE AMOUNT NEEDED AND TWO TO FOUR GALLONS RAN ONTO THE FLOOR. A COMPANY SERVICEMAN RESPONDED IMMEDIATELY AND PUT DOWN ABSORBENT AND SWEPT UP THE AREA. CUSTOMER DEMANDED A NIGHT'S LODGING AND MEALS, STATING HE COULDN'T STAY IN THE HOUSE. CALLS WERE MADE TO THE EPA AND THE FIRE DEPARTMENT. FIRE DEPARTMENT SAW NO NEED TO RESPOND. EPA FOUND NOTHING SERIOUS ENOUGH TO REQUIRE ACTION. WE REFUSE TO CONTINUE TO SERVICE THE CUSTOMER. THE AMOUNT OF OVERFLOW WAS APPROXIMATELY TWO-FOUR GALLONS.

column168: ON NOV 5, 2001 WE HAD A MINOR ANHYDROUS AMMONIA RELEASE WHICH ONLY AMOUNTED TO A SMALL WET SPOT ON THE EDGE OF THE BLACKTOP. THIS SPILL WAS CAUSED WHEN THE NURSE TANK ROLLED ON ITS SIDE. AT THE TIME OF THE ACCIDENT WE HAD A VERY STRONG WIND. AS THE DRIVER PASSED A GROVE OF TREES THE WIND PULLED HIM OVER ENOUGH TO GET OFF THE BLACKTOP AND ON THE EDGE OF THE ROAD RESULTING IN THE TANK ROLLING OVER. WHEN ALL WAS OVER THERE WAS A TIRE THAT BLEW OUT ON THE TRAILER. THERE IS THE POSSIBILITY THAT THE TIRE WAS PART OF THE PROBLEM BUT I FEEL THE TIRE BLEW OUT ONLY BECAUSE OF THE STRESS PUT ON IT BY THE TANK BOUNCING ON THE EDGE OF THE ROADWAY. THIS ACCIDENT MAY HAVE BEEN THE RESULT OF FAULTY EQUIPMENT BUT I FEEL IT WAS MORE DO TO THE WIND. IF YOU HAVE ANY OTHER QUESTIONS YOU CAN CONTACT ME AT 712-724-6171

column168: ASARCO, INC. HAS A COPPER SMELTER WITH SULFURIC ACID PLANT AT HAYDEN, AZ. NINETY-THREE PERCENT SULFURIC ACID IS AVAILABLE FOR SALE TO INDUSTRIAL AND AGRICULTURAL CLIENTS WITH DELIVERY VIA MOTOR CARRIER AND RAIL TANK CARS. CHALUM INDUSTRY, THE CONSIGNEE, AT SACATON, AZ, 88 MILES FROM HAYDEN, USES SULFURIC ACID TO MAKE ALUMINUM SULFATE (ALUM) FOR WATER TREATMENT IN PHOENIX, AZ.  THE CARRIER USED 3,500 GALLON, MC 412, CARGO TANKS, 41 FEET OVERALL LENGTH WITH A 20 INCH TYONA BETTS FILLER DOME LOCATED 12 FEET FORWARD OF THE REAR OF THE TANK.  THE FILLER DOME LID HAS A 3/4" X 3/4" HYPOLON GASKET THAT MATES WITH THE 20" DIAMETER 1/4" THICK RISER AT THE TOP OF THE VESSEL.  THE DOME LID IS ASME AND IS SECURED WITH SIX SCREW-DOWN DOGS.  ALSO IN THE SPILL DAM, ROLLOVER PROTECTED FILLER DOME AREA, IS A 1" AIR INLET PIPE WITH 1" STAINLESS BALL VALVE AND CAPPED CHICAGO AIR COUPLER. THE DRIVER, JOHN D. ALLISON, SSN:600-01-6043, ARRIVED AT THE ASARCO ACID PLANT AND WEIGHED THE TRACTOR-TRAILER EMPTY OR TARE WEIGHT.  HE THEN WENT BACK INTO THE LOADING RACK WHICH HAS A BACKWARD PLATFORM.  THIS ONE MATES WITH THE LEFT OR STREET SIDE OF THE MC412 WHILE THE DRIVER WORK PLATFORM IS ON THE RIGHT SIDE.  ONCE THE VEHICLE WAS PARKED, CHALKED, AND THE BRAKES WERE SET, THE DRIVER PUT ON FULL PERSONAL PROTECTIVE GEAR, OPENED THE FILLER DOME LID, INSERTED THE LOADING SPOUT, AND PLACED A COMPANY SUPPLIED METAL STRAP WITH A U-SHAPED UPPER END OVER THE 1/4" RISER OF THE TANK. THIS METAL STRAP IS 1" WIDE BY 1/16" THICK AND IS USED AS A LOADING MARKER IN THE 3,500 GALLON VESSEL.  ASARCO WOULD NOT ALLOW TRUCKS TO LEAVE WITH A GROSS THAT EXCEEDED 80,000 POUNDS SO THE PORTABLE LOADING MARKER HAS LIQUID LEVEL INDICATORS FOR ALL THE ACID PLANTS WHERE WE LOADED.  THE DRIVER THEN OPENED VALVES AND STARTED THE PUMP TO DELIVER THE DESIRED LIQUID LEVEL ON THE MARKER.  WHEN LOADED, HE STOPPED THE PUMP TO DELIVER THE DESIRED LIQUID LEVEL ON THE MARKER.  WHEN LOADED, HE STOPPED THE PUMP, CLOSED THE VALVES, FAILED TO REMOVE THE U-SHAPED MARKER STICK, CLOSED AND SECURED THE DOME LID AND CHECKED TO INSURE THE 1" BALL VALVE (AIR INLET) WAS CLOSED.  HE THEN RE-WEIGHED FOR HIS GROSS WEIGHT AND PROCEEDED TO THE SECURITY OFFICE FOR BILLS OF LADING.  A FINAL CHECK OF THE LOWER AND UPPER OPENINGS OF THE TRANSPORT WAS MADE AT THIS POINT BECAUSE THE VEHICLE HAD BEEN MOVED AND AN UNSECURED OPENING SHOULD SHOW EVIDENCE OF RELEASE OR LEAK PRIOR TO LEAVING THE SHIPPER'S PROPERTY.  ASARCO LOADS MANY CARRIERS IN A 24 HOUR PERIOD AND SOME LOADS GO NORTH ON AZ 177, THE 31  MILES TO SUPERIOR, AZ, AND U.S. HIGHWAY 60. AZ 177 RUNS THROUGH THE LINES THAT REQUIRE HAZ MAT TRUCKS TO STOP BOTH LOADED AND EMPTY.  IN ADDITION TO THE RAILROAD TRACK STOPS, THE ROUTE HAS SEVERAL LONG MOUNTAINOUS UP-HILL GRADES.  THE FIRST STARTS AT MP 152.8 AND RUNS FOR TWO MILES UP HILL AT A 7% GRADE.  THE NEXT IS A MORE SEVERE 10% GRADE AND IT STARTS AT ABOUT 158.0 AND RUNS TO MP 161.0, ABOUT 6 MILES SOUTH OF SUPERIOR. # 2 HEATING FUEL DELIVERY TO EXTERIOR FILL PIPE BUT INTERIOR STORAGE TANK HAD BEEN REMOVED.
